<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOLLYWOOD AND BLACK AMERICANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Writer Stein makes a good point when he describes Hollywood's reluctance to 
cast black Americans in positive and inspirational roles. I agree totally and 
would like to extend his point to include the responsibility of today's black 
producers to generate movies with a positive and meaningful purpose. 
</P>
<P>
On a recent trip to the movies I saw the film "Do the Right Thing," a movie 
that has been mentioned as the best picture of the year. In my opinion this is 
one of the all-time worst movies to come out of Hollywood. It is insulting and 
degrading to the black community. I don't deny the existence of the black 
experience the movie describes, but why must all our black-produced movies 
bring the same negative message? 
</P>
<P>
If black producers can't come up with something positive from the black 
American life style, how can we expect others to do so? I believe our black 
producers have a responsibility to present some of the positive experiences 
that are occurring every day in the black American life style. 
</P>
<P>
RAYMOND M. STEWART 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
