<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONSUMER VIEWS: CONSUMERS; 
</P>
<P>
GUIDE FOR THE DISGRUNTLED MAY HAVE YOUR NUMBER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DONALD G. CAMPBELL, Campbell is a syndicated columnist and former Times 
staff writer. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: Like a lot of people, I frequently feel the need to complain to 
someone -- anyone -- when I feel that I've been ripped off. But where do I 
start? Writing to a department store, for instance, is like dropping the letter 
into a big hole. Any suggestions? -- G.M. 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Even with a Rolodex filled with consumer-oriented contacts, I know and 
share your bafflement. You should find a new publication by San Francisco-based 
Consumer Action invaluable, however. It's the 1989-1990 edition of the group's 
16-page pamphlet, "Consumer Services Guide," and it includes the addresses and 
telephone numbers of regulatory and law-enforcement government agencies, 
business-sponsored complaint resolution offices, nonprofit information and 
referral organizations and agencies that offer free, or low-cost, legal 
assistance. I use it constantly. 
</P>
<P>
You can get a copy by sending $1 for postage and handling to: Consumer Action, 
116 New Montgomery St., San Francisco, Calif. 94105. Free copies of the guide 
are available in bulk to community-based organizations. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I was deeply disappointed in the answer you gave recently on the way the 
California Lottery publicizes its large prizes -- a deceptive and fraudulent 
practice. Instead of condemning it for the deception that it is, you condoned 
it, and you further muddied the waters with a discussion of taxes. 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps the most basic concept in all of economics is the notion of the time 
value of money. A dollar to be paid tomorrow is not worth as much as a dollar 
paid today. The only way you can call that lottery prize "a million dollars" is 
to assume that interest rates are zero. 
</P>
<P>
The quote that a lottery representative gave you: "the money we spend to pay a 
$1-million prize is exactly half that," is a bald-faced admission of that lie. 
Your newspaper could end the deception tomorrow. All it would take would be for 
you to agree that whenever you run a story about a lottery prize, the number in 
the article and the number in the headline should be the present value of the 
award. -- K.G.M. 
</P>
<P>
A: I wouldn't presume to argue with a university professor of mathematics even 
if I didn't agree with you in principle. 
</P>
<P>
I quite understand the concept of the value of money and I am not condoning the 
lottery or the people charged with conducting it. I explained the state's 
rationale for doing it the way it does it -- to keep public interest in the 
lottery at a fever pitch. I don't recall saying that I approved of this 
fun-with-figures way of presenting it. 
</P>
<P>
I agree with you -- any state lottery is a piece of fluff right from the time 
you buy a $1 ticket, only 50 cents of which goes into the "pot" in the first 
place. And, with odds of 14- to 16-million-to-1, this is "gambling" in about 
the same way that diving blindfolded, and armed with a spear, into an 
Olympic-sized swimming pool containing two guppies is "going fishing." 
</P>
<P>
This is pure fantasy. The state knows it and the lottery players know it and, 
speaking of odds, I will lay odds that the next person hitting a "$10-million" 
top prize doesn't give a diddly what the "present value" of that $10 million 
really is -- he sees 20 annual payments of (before taxes) $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
Q: Last April, American Continental Corp. declared bankruptcy. I am 76 years 
old and my wife is 67. We had invested $45,000 in this company. It was money 
earned with hard work to provide an extra income to supplement our Social 
Security. About 25,000 other investors were involved, and the company used the 
money to buy luxury cars and houses. 
</P>
<P>
We don't know where to turn. Is there any law in this country to protect the 
little investor? -- Z.L. 
</P>
<P>
A: I wish we could be more optimistic here, but it's going to take a long time 
for the federal regulators to muddle through the complex, overlapping affairs 
of American Continental and its many subsidiaries -- the principal one being 
Lincoln Savings, which did, indeed, sell about $200 million in bonds to 
individual investors. And most of those investors, unfortunately, are in the 
same boat as you. Bondholders like you fall under the heading of "unsecured 
creditors" and, in the pay-back line, are behind the other creditors holding 
so-called "secured" claims on the company. 
</P>
<P>
"Laws to protect the little investor," alas, don't really work. With any 
investment there must be some degree of risk. There are laws, of course, 
requiring that the degree of that risk be fully disclosed. And this is where 
tightening up is called for. All you can really do, I'm afraid, is hope that 
enough of American Continental's assets can be sold off to get the bondholders 
at least a portion of their (your) money back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
