<HEADLINE>
<P>
BUSH VOWS JUSTICE IN BOMBING DEATHS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Bush on Tuesday praised Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s courage in the 
face of threats and promised to "bring to justice the bigots" responsible for a 
wave of bombings against civil rights leaders two decades after King's death. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Benjamin L. Hooks, executive director of the NAACP, a prime target of the 
hate campaign, emerged from the Oval Office saying he was "fairly satisfied" 
with federal efforts to solve the bombings, but was seeking further assurance 
"that from the presidency down there is a sense of urgency." 
</P>
<P>
Bush invited civil rights leaders and students to the White House to witness 
his signing of a proclamation in connection with Monday's holiday marking 
King's birthday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
BUSH, GEORGE; CRIMINAL JUSTICE; HATE CRIMES; TERRORISM; THREATS; BOMBINGS -- 
GEORGIA; BOMBINGS -- ALABAMA; HOLIDAYS; KING, MARTIN LUTHER JR; CIVIL RIGHTS 
MOVEMENT 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
